{{distinguish|Impressionism in art}} An '''artist's impression''' or '''artist's interpretation''' is the representation of an object or a scene created by an artist, when no other accurate representation is available. It could be an image, a sound, a video or a model. Artist's impressions are often created to represent concepts and objects that cannot be seen by the naked eye; that are very big, very small, in the past, in the future, fictional, or otherwise abstract in other ways. For example, in architecture, artists' impressions are used to showcase the design of planned buildings and associated landscape.<ref name="BobMargaret2004">{{cite book | author1=Bob Giddings | author2=Margaret Horne | title=Artists' Impressions in Architectural Design | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ekhXDjNF2bkC&pg=PA1 | accessdate=24 May 2013 | date=9 March 2004 | publisher=Taylor & Francis | isbn=978-0-203-36246-4 | pages=1–}}</ref> Artists' impressions are particularly prominent in [[space art]].<ref name="NASA's Space Art Program">{{Cite web |url=http://newatlas.com/how-are-planets-painted/42763/ |title=Artist's Impression: How to Paint a Planet |last=Powell |first=Dominic |date=2016-04-16 |website=New Atlas}}</ref>
